You are scoring one Veyru team's link-channel communication against a fixed ontology of communication-pattern features. The ontology was distilled from open-coding many runs; your job is to decide, for each ontology category, how strongly this run's link messages exhibit that feature.

For every category in the ontology below, emit one ``CategoryConfidence`` entry with:
- ``category_id`` — exactly the id from the ontology (case-sensitive).
- ``confidence`` — a float in [0.0, 1.0]. **Score the magnitude of evidence, not your own certainty:**
  - 0.0 — feature is plainly absent across the entire run.
  - ~0.3 — incidental or borderline; maybe one round, ambiguous.
  - ~0.6 — feature appears clearly in multiple rounds but not pervasively.
  - 0.9–1.0 — feature is a dominant, sustained property of the team's protocol.
- ``justification`` — one or two sentences citing specific link-channel evidence (round numbers, brief quotes) or its absence.

You MUST emit one entry per category, in the order they are listed. Do not skip a category just because the feature is absent — a low confidence with a short "absent" justification is the expected output.

The two agents have asymmetric inputs each round (rendered explicitly below):
- The OBSERVER only sees raw observable-symptoms text. No motif names, no procedures, no stellar reading.
- The ENGINEER sees a per-motif stellar table (motif → procedure with parameters filled in) plus a static motif/canonical-symptom-phrase list from their system prompt.
Use this when deciding whether the team is encoding symptoms, treatments, both, or neither — and remember that an observer who emits motif-side or treatment-side encodings must have learned the mapping from earlier link messages or postmortem coordination.

